{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473460"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2441"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2441"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.18,0.12,0.17,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27824"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2134"},{"type":"tags","id":"2142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2917"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 7-year-old boy presents to his General Practice clinic with his parents with progressive swelling of his face for two days. He experienced an upper respiratory tract infection seven days ago. His past medical history is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vitals are within the normal range. On examination, there is mild oedema detected in the lower extremities. The examination of other systems is normal. Investigations show a normal complete blood count, renal function tests and liver function tests. Urine examination shows proteinuria and oval fatty bodies are seen on microscopy. A 24-hour urine collection test gives the value of protein to be 3.7 g/day. Ultrasound of the abdomen is unremarkable. A kidney biopsy is ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological findings is most likely to be seen in this patient on light microscopy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apple green birefringence under polarized light","Crescents of fibrin and monocytes in glomeruli","Eosinophilic nodular glomerulosclerosis","Hypercellularity and enlargement of glomeruli","Normal glomeruli"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with oedema, proteinuria \u0026gt;3.5 g per day and fatty casts is suffering from nephrotic syndrome. Minimal change disease (MCD) is a type of nephrotic syndrome that is more common in children aged \u0026lt;10 years and is often idiopathic. A few cases may present following an infection (as seen in this patient), immunisation, or any other immune stimulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCD is postulated to occur from the cytokine-mediated injury of the foot processes of the podocytes. This effects the negative charge of the glomerular basement membrane and allows albumin to be lost into the renal tubules and excreted in the urine. Decreased albumin leads to decreased oncotic pressure in vessels, thus resulting in oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESince this disease is mainly due to the disruption of the charge barrier, urinalysis primarily shows proteinuria only. Haematuria is not seen in a nephrotic syndrome. Fatty casts/oval fat bodies may also be seen on microscopy. Light microscopy of the histologic sample obtained from a kidney biopsy may reveal \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal glomeruli.\u003C/strong\u003E The immunofluorescence studies are unremarkable while electron microscopy shows effacement of the podocyte foot processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmyloid deposition in the mesangium shows \u003Cstrong\u003Eapple-green birefringence\u003C/strong\u003E when the histologic sample is stained with a congo red stain and is viewed \u003Cstrong\u003Eunder polarized light. \u003C/strong\u003ESystemic amyloidosis results in this disease. This patient has no history and signs and symptoms of diseases resulting in amyloidosis (e.g multiple myeloma, IBD, etc).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlomeruli containing \u003Cstrong\u003Ecrescents consisting of fibrin, monocytes, \u003C/strong\u003Emacrophages, and other plasma proteins are seen in rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN). However, it is a nephritic syndrome and is associated with rapidly deteriorating renal functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic nodular glomerulosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E (i.e. Kimmelstiel-Wilson nodules) is a feature of diabetic nephropathy. This patient\u0027s young age with no history and signs or symptoms of diabetes make this diagnosis highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis also develops after group A streptococcal infection (e.g pharyngitis, impetigo) and is characterized by \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypercellularity and glomerular enlargement.\u003C/strong\u003E However, it is a nephritic syndrome and is characterized by hypertension, haematuria, and RBC casts in urine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Minimal change disease (MCD) is a type of nephrotic syndrome that is more common in children aged \u003C10 years and is often idiopathic."],"references":["Vivarelli M, Massella L, Ruggiero B, Emma F. Minimal Change Disease. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2017;12(2):332-345. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5293332/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27824"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2441"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27824"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-21T11:13:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-21T11:13:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2441"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.eme